 Mozambique -- t13 NORWEGIAN INVESTORS AND THEIR AGENTS IN COLONIAL KENYA -- t14 SCANDINAVIAN AGENTS AND ENTREPRENEURS IN THE SCRAMBLE FOR ETHNOGRAPHICA DURING COLONIAL EXPANSION IN THE CONGO -- tAfterword HER OG NÅ (HERE AND NOW) History and the Idea of Globalization -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNorwegians in colonial Africa and Oceania had varying aspirations and adapted in different ways to changing social, political and geographical circumstances in foreign, colonial settings. They included Norwegian shipowners, captains, and diplomats; traders and whalers along the African coast and in Antarctica; large-scale plantation owners in Mozambique and Hawai’i; big business men in South Africa; jacks of all trades in the Solomon Islands; timber merchants on Zanzibar’ coffee farmers in Kenya; and King Leopold’s footmen in Congo. This collection reveals narratives of the colonial era that are often ignored or obscured by the national histories of former colonial powers. It charts the entrepreneurial routes chosen by various Norwegians and the places they ventured, while demonstrating the importance of recognizing the complicity of such “non-colonial colonials” for understanding the complexity of colonial history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aColonieszAfricaxEconomic conditions. 0aColonieszOceaniaxEconomic conditions. 0aEntrepreneurshipzAfricaxHistory. 0aEntrepreneurshipzOceaniaxHistory. 0aNorwegianszAfricaxHistory. 0aNorwegianszOceaniaxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh  aColonial History.1 aAngell, Svein Ivar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBang, Anne K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato